__NOTOC__ [[File:What happened then stories (1918) (14566206889).jpg|thumb|Jack meets a fairy in ''[[Jack and the Beanstalk]]'']]
'''Jack''' is an [[archetype|archetypal]] [[Cornish people|Cornish]] and [[English folklore|English]] [[hero]] and [[stock character]] appearing in [[legend]]s, [[fairy tale]]s, and [[nursery rhyme]]s, generally portrayed as a [[youth|young adult]]. Unlike [[morality play|moralizing fairy heroes]], Jack is often portrayed as lazy or foolish, but through the use of cleverness and tricks he usually emerges triumphant. In this way, he may resemble a [[trickster]].
Some of the most famous are "[[Jack and the Beanstalk]]", "[[Jack Frost]]", "[[Jack the Giant Killer]]", "[[Little Jack Horner]]" and "[[This Is the House That Jack Built]]". While these heroes are not necessarily congruous, their concepts are related and in some instances interchangeable. The notion of "Jack" is closely related and sometimes identical to the English hero [[John (given name)|John]]. He also corresponds with the [[German folklore|German]] [[Hans in Luck|Hans]] (or Hänsel) and the [[Russian folklore|Russian]] Iván.<ref>{{cite book |author=Jack Zipes |year=2004 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sbmmrhmwix0C&dq=jack+hero+-+english+fairy+tales+-15th+century&source=gbs_navlinks_s |title=Speaking Out: Storytelling and Creative Drama for Children |page=129 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-0-4159-6660-3}}</ref>
"Jack tales" are also popular in [[Appalachia#Folklore|Appalachian]] folklore.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.ferrum.edu/applit//articles/wondertales.htm |title=Wonder Tales in Appalachia |publisher=AppLit |author=Grace Toney Edwards |date=July 1, 2010 |accessdate=2015-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9CSxlgEACAAJ&dq=Journey+Through+Fantasy+Literature:+A+Resource+Guide+for+Teachers&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tzerVLDRNYiuogSskYGACg&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA |title=Journey Through Fantasy Literature: A Resource Guide for Teachers |author=Roberta T. Herrin |publisher=Department of English, College of Arts and Science, East Tennessee State University |year=1992 |isbn=}}</ref> [[Richard Chase (folklorist)|Richard Chase]], an American Folklorist, collected in his book "The Jack Tales" many popular Appalachian Jack tales as told by descendants of Council Harmon. Council Harmon's grandfather, Cutliff Harmon, is thought to very possibly be the one who originally brought the Jack tales to America.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=P34ONYQuaLoC&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=Cutliff+Harmon&source=bl&ots=FvlAHU38_S&sig=cSK2VF4lQ01rKL2ajJ-P42Z1VgY&hl=en&ei=ZCNqTKuuDYP78Aa-xsGzBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=Cutliff%20Harmon&f=false Betty N. Smith, ''Jane Hicks Gentry: A Singer Among Singers''], University Press of Kentucky (1998), {{ISBN|978-0-8131-0936-7}} , page 15.</ref><ref>Julia Taylor Ebel and Orville Hicks, ''Orville Hicks: Mountain Stories, Mountain Roots'', University Press of Kentucky (1998), {{ISBN|978-1-9332-5102-8}}, page 11.</ref> As pointed out by folklorist [[Herbert Halpert]], the Appalachian Jack tales are an oral tradition as opposed to written, and like many Appalachian folksongs, trace back to sources in England.<ref>Richard Chase, ed., ''The Jack Tales'', Houghton Mifflin Co., 1943, {{ISBN|0-395-06694-8}}. "Told by R. M. Ward and his kindred in the Beech Mountain section of Western North Carolina and by other descendants of Council Harmon (1803-1896) elsewhere in The Southern Mountains; with three tales from Wise County, Virginia. Set down from these sources and edited by [[Richard Chase (folklorist)|Richard Chase]]; with an appendix compiled by [[Herbert Halpert]]; and illustrated by Berkeley Williams, Jr."</ref> For instance, where the English original would feature a king or other noble, the Appalachian Jack tale version would have a sheriff. Some stories feature Jack's brothers, Will and Tom. Some Jack tales feature themes that trace to Germanic folk tales.
==See also== *[[Jack of all trades, master of none]] *[[Jack in the green]] *[[Jack-o'-lantern]] *[[Jack o' Kent]] *[[Jack and Jill (nursery rhyme)|Jack and Jill]] *[[Jack Be Nimble]] *[[Jack Sprat]] *[[Stingy Jack]] *[[Spring-heeled Jack]] *[[Ivan the Fool]] *[[Jack (name)]] *[[Jack (disambiguation)]] *[[Jack and the Beanstalk]] *[[Jack Horner (comics)]] *[[Jack (Fight Club)]]
