{{italic title}}
[[File:Budapest Rearing Horse and Mounted Warrior, right side, by E.C.Rae.png|thumb|upright=1.35|1945 black-and-white photo]]
The '''''Rearing Horse and Mounted Warrior''''' or '''''Budapest horse''''' is a [[bronze]] sculpture attributed to [[Leonardo da Vinci]]. Depicting [[Francis I of France]] on a [[destrier]] horse, it is estimated to have been cast from a clay or wax model in the first half of the 16th century.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.szepmuveszeti.hu/adatlap_eng/mounted_warrior_leonardo_da_vinci_2778 |title=Mounted Warrior |publisher=Budapest Museum of Fine Arts |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Budapest Museum of Fine Arts}} }}</ref> The sculpture is in the permanent exhibit of the [[Museum of Fine Arts (Budapest)|Budapest Museum of Fine Arts]].

== Description ==

The bronze statuette consists of the horse and a detachable rider. It has an applied green patina on top of black paint patina, typical of Renaissance works.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Die Reiterdarstellungen Leonardos und die Budapester Bronzestatuette |last=Meller |first=Simon |year=1916 |journal=Jahrbuch der Königlich Preussischen Kunstsammlungen |volume=37 |url=https://www.digizeitschriften.de/download/PPN523141572_0037/PPN523141572_0037___LOG_0030.pdf |jstor=25168823 |pages=213–250 |language=German |ref=harv}}</ref> Both parts are hollow, and attached together are 24&nbsp;cm high, 15&nbsp;cm wide, and 28&nbsp;cm long ({{convert|24|cm|in|disp=out}} by {{convert|15|cm|in|disp=out}} by {{convert|28|cm|in|disp=out}}),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/2009/budapesthorse/budapesthorsefull.shtm |title=The Budapest Horse: A Leonardo da Vinci Puzzle |publisher=National Gallery of Art |date=2009 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|NGA|2009b}} |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105002015/http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/2009/budapesthorse/budapesthorsefull.shtm |archivedate=5 November 2016 |df= }}</ref> and weigh {{convert|{{#expr:1.95+0.44}}|kg|lb}}.<ref>{{cite journal |title=La statuette équestre de Léonard de Vinci |last=Aggházy |first=Mária G. |year=1971 |journal=Bulletin du Musée Hongrois des Beaux-Arts |number=36 |pages=77 |url=https://library.hungaricana.hu/en/view/ORSZ_SZEP_Kozl_036/?pg=78&layout=s |publisher=Museum of Fine Arts |location=Budapest |language=French |ref=harv}}</ref> The parts were cast separately, including the horse's rump and tail section that was used to extract the core, but nevertheless at the same time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nga.gov/press/exh/3055/index.shtm |title=Leonardo da Vinci Puzzle Examined by Research and Exhibition of Budapest Horse and Related Bronzes at National Gallery of Art, Washington |publisher=National Gallery of Art |date=25 June 2009 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|NGA|2009a}} |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402041256/http://www.nga.gov/press/exh/3055/index.shtm |archivedate=2 April 2013 }}</ref> There is minimal trace of finishing on the statuette; many of the holes and casting flaws on both the horse and the rider have not been chiseled off or filled, which suggests an intent of preserving a model rather than making a final cast.<ref>{{cite book |title=Making and Moving Sculpture in Early Modern Italy |editor-last=Helmstutler Di Dio |editor-first=Kelley |chapter=The Budapest Horse: Beyond the Leonardo da Vinci Question |last1=Sturman |first1=Shelley |last2=May |first2=Katherine |last3=Luchs |first3=Alison |date=28 October 2015 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing |location=Farnham |isbn=978-1-4724-6090-5 |page=34 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aAWgCgAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}</ref>

The rider is wearing a Greek-style helmet with its visor tipped up, encircled by a crown, with a serpent-tailed dragon on the back.<ref>{{cite book |title=Leonardo's equestrian statuette |last=Aggházy |first=Mária G. |translator-last=Simon |translator-first=Agnes |year=1989 |publisher=Akadémiai Kiadó |location=Budapest |isbn=9630539519 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FrsxAAAAIAAJ |ref=harv |page=10}}</ref> He is holding a shield in his left hand, and originally had a sword or a lance in his right hand, but only the hilt is now left.{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=34}} Similar horses and riders, some in exactly the same position, are depicted in many of Leonardo's studies of horses owned by the Milanese nobleman [[Galéas de Saint-Séverin]].{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=34}} The depiction of the rider is less defined than the horse or Leonardo's other works.{{sfn|Sturman|May|Luchs|2015|p=29}}

Hungarian art historian Mária Aggházy noticed a resemblance between the content-looking rider and the young [[Francis I of France]], soon to be king, and Leonardo's patron from his later years.{{sfn|Sturman|May|Luchs|2015|p=29}} Francis was an avid participant in [[jousting]] tournaments, which in the more entertaining but also more dangerous French style were run with less armour and other equipment than in Italy. Aggházy theorised that the rider's light clothing, likely after a victorious duel, demonstrated bravery on Francis's part as he followed the [[Chivalry|chivalrous]] ideals of the [[Nine Worthies]].{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|pp=36–37}}

== History ==

[[File:Francois Ier by Jean Clouet.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Young Francis I by [[Jean Clouet]] c.1515]]
In 1516, after invitations from King Francis I of France and his predecessor, [[Louis XII of France]], Leonardo moved to France and entered the service of Francis I. Art chronicler [[Gian Paolo Lomazzo]], close to Leonardo's heirs, wrote in 1584 that Leonardo had made several models of horses for Francis. This statuette is believed to be one of them.<ref>{{cite book |title=Leonardo Da Vinci: Drawings of Horses and Other Animals from the Royal Library at Windsor Castle |last=Pedretti |first=Carlo |date=1984 |publisher=Johnson Reprint Corporation |isbn=0-384-45282-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HGlQAAAAMAAJ |page=74 |ref=harv}}</ref>

Towards the end of his life, Leonardo was working on several equestrian monuments, and did several studies of horses on worksheets that have been preserved in the [[Royal Collection]] in [[Windsor Castle]]. This statuette was depicted in sketches from c.1490<ref>{{Royal Collection|912283|Folio RL 12283}} Retrieved 28 March 2017. Cited in [[#{{sfnref|Aggházy|1989}}|Aggházy 1989]].</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=An Overview of Leonardo's Career and Projects Until c.1500 |editor-last=Farago |editor-first=Claire J. |chapter=Leonardo's Sforza Monument and Cinquecento Sculpture |last=Bush |first=Virginia L. |date=1999 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8153-2934-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=fMDoImNWqHQC&pg=PA410 410] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fMDoImNWqHQC |ref=harv}}</ref> and c.1517–1518<ref>{{Royal Collection|912354|Folio RL 12354}} Retrieved 28 March 2017. Cited in [[#{{sfnref|Aggházy|1989}}|Aggházy 1989]].</ref><ref>{{Royal Collection|912331|Folio RL 12331}} Retrieved 28 March 2017. Cited in [[#{{sfnref|Clark|Pedretti|1968}}|Clark & Pedretti 1968]].</ref> with and without the rider. By then Leonardo was unable to continue with artwork much beyond sketches, but did for instance supervise bronze casting of statues at the king's [[Palace of Fontainebleau]].{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=25}}

By 1540, Leonardo's follower [[Leone Leoni]] was also commissioned to create an equestrian statuette while he was a [[court painter|court sculptor]] to [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]], who governed Milan at the time.{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=46}} In 1549 and 1550, Leoni sent several letters to [[Antoine Perrenot de Granvelle]] requesting that Leonardo's statuette from the king's court be sent back to him.{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=48}} An equestrian bronze model was recorded in the Leoni collection at their home [[Casa degli Omenoni]] before the collection was dispersed by 1620.{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=40}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Leone Leoni's Collection in the Casa Degli Omenoni, Milan: The Inventory of 1609 |last=Helmstutler Di Dio |first=Kelley |date=August 2003 |journal=[[The Burlington Magazine]] |volume=145 |number=1205 |jstor=20073166 |page=572–578 |ref=harv}}</ref>

The outline of the statuette also features in a c.1545 [[Scroll (art)|scrollwork]] from the Fontainebleau workshops of Francis I. The scrollwork has a detailed design for the decoration of a horse's [[chanfron]] head armour to be used in jousting.<ref>{{cite book |title=Leonardo: A Study in Chronology and Style |last=Pedretti |first=Carlo |date=1973 |publisher=University of California Press |location=Berkeley |isbn=0-520-02420-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TgXMajWbVfcC |page=174 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=46}}<ref>Stored in the [[Staatliche Graphische Sammlung München]]. ''14.703''. Pictured in [[#{{sfnref|Aggházy|1989}}|Aggházy 1989]], Fig. 41, and a portion in [[#{{sfnref|Aggházy|1971}}|Aggházy 1971]], page [https://library.hungaricana.hu/en/view/ORSZ_SZEP_Kozl_036/?pg=63&layout=s 62], and [[#{{sfnref|Aggházy|1972}}|Aggházy 1972]], page 123, top right.</ref>

=== Modern history ===

[[File:Ferenczy István 1810 crop.png|thumb|upright=0.75|István Ferenczy in 1810 by Sándor Ádám Ehrenreich]]
In 1818, a Hungarian sculptor, [[István Ferenczy]], moved from Hungary to Rome and spent 6 years there as a student of the acclaimed sculptors [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]] and [[Antonio Canova]].{{sfn|Meller|1916|p=243}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mno.hu/migr_1834/szobrok-a-falbol-772194 |title=Leonardo da Vinci és a Ferenczy István-hagyaték: egy szenzációs művészeti pör |last=Ferch |first=Magda |publisher=[[Magyar Nemzet]] |language=Hungarian |date=21 September 2002 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref=harv}}</ref> During his stay in Rome, Ferenczy gathered a collection of 82 works of art, including this statuette, which he had acquired in the mistaken belief that it was a Greek work. In 1846 he prepared an inventory with the intention of selling the collection to the Hungarian state, still with the statuette as an ancient work from Athens, but the sale did not go through.{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=54}}{{sfn|Sturman|May|Luchs|2015|p=41}} As Ferenczy's will stated that the crates of his collection were not to be opened for 50 years, the collection remained untouched for a long time after his death in 1856.{{sfn|Ferch|2002}} The family reached a deal with the [[Museum of Fine Arts (Budapest)|Museum of Fine Arts in Budapest]] and sold the collection to them in 1914, still none the wiser about the statuette.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/szepmuveszeti/docs/issuu_rsz_eng_web_jav |title=History of the Sculpture Collection of the Museum of Fine Arts Budapest |publisher=Museum of Fine Arts, Budapest |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Museum of Fine Arts|2014}}
}}</ref>{{sfn|NGA|2009a}} After discovering its provenance, the heirs sued the museum for a misleading sale and poor payments during the [[Hungary in World War I#Aftermath|aftermath of World War I]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://elsovh.hu/leonardo-da-vinci-szobra-budapesten-bukkant-fel/ |title=Leonardo da Vinci szobra Budapesten bukkant fel? |last=Takács |first=Róbert |website=Frontlines and Hinterland |publisher=Politikatörténeti Intézet Közhasznú Nonprofit Kft.t |language=Hungarian |date=2015 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref=harv}}</ref>

Simon Meller, the curator of the Budapest museum, began exploring the statuette with more knowledge of Leonardo's equestrian works. He came to the conclusion that the style of the statuette is consistent with Leonardo's other works, particularly those in the studies for [[The Battle of Anghiari (painting)|the painting of ''The Battle of Anghiari'']] and the [[Gian Giacomo Trivulzio|Trivulzio]] monument. He attributed the statuette to Leonardo da Vinci for the first time since the 17th century, and published it in a 1916 journal of the museums in the [[Prussia]]n region.{{sfn|NGA|2009a}}{{sfn|Meller|1916|pp=243–244}} To mark the occasion, another sculptor in the Ferenczy family, [[Béni Ferenczy]], gifted Meller a commemorative medal with a [[relief]] of the statuette.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://100hires.hu/cikkek/ferenczy-beni |title=Ferenczy Béni |website=100 híres |publisher=Hungarian National Digital Archive and Film Institute |language=Hungarian |accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref> The statuette became a permanent exhibit in the museum in the 1920s.{{sfn|Museum of Fine Arts|2014}}

The 1940s were a tumultuous time for Europe's artworks, with the statuette, the [[Holy Crown of Hungary]], and many other works of art captured in the [[Nazi plunder]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artmagazin.hu/artmagazin_hirek/magyar_mukincsek_a_muncheni_collecting_pointban_iii..3402.html?pageid=119 |title=Magyar műkincsek a müncheni Collecting Pointban III |last=Kovács |first=Ágnes |website=Artmagazin Online |date=August 2015 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |language=Hungarian |ref=harv}}</ref> During World War II, Hungary joined the [[Axis powers]] in 1940.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.euronews.com/2015/05/05/how-world-war-ii-shaped-modern-hungary |title=How World War II shaped modern Hungary |last=Pálfi |first=Rita |date=5 May 2015 |publisher=Euronews |accessdate=3 April 2017 |ref=harv}}</ref> In September 1942, Russia unexpectedly bombed Budapest.<ref>{{cite book |title=Hungary at War: Civilians and Soldiers in World War II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LQ2j2_wcWxMC&pg=PA36 |last=Eby |first=Cecil D. |year=2010 |publisher=Pennsylvania State University Press |isbn=9780271040882 |page=36}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Russian planes bomb Budapest |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11994048 |date=7 September 1942 |work=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |issue=29,964 |page=1}}</ref> The museum began the protection of their works of art by packing them into crates and moving them to lower floors. Considered one of the most precious works in the museum's collection, the statuette and the works of [[Old Master]]s were taken further west from the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] to [[Veszprém]] in early 1943.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Balogh |first=Jolán |year=1954 |title=La Collection des Sculptures Anciennes |journal=Bulletin du Musée Hongrois des Beaux-Arts |url=https://library.hungaricana.hu/en/view/ORSZ_SZEP_Kozl_004/?pg=61&layout=r |publisher=Museum of Fine Arts |location=Budapest |number=4 |page=58 |language=French |ref=harv}}</ref> Once Hungary started attempts to reach peace with the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]], Germany [[Operation Margarethe|invaded the country]] in March 1944.{{sfn|Pálfi|2015}}

The Museum of Fine Arts was under the control of the Ministry of Education, where the newly installed [[Ferenc Rajniss]], sympathetic to the Nazi rule, ordered the majority of the museum's artwork to be sent to Austria. The director of the museum had no trace of their whereabouts.{{sfn|Kovács|2015}} In late 1944, the [[Red Army]] captured Budapest in the [[Budapest Offensive]], and damaged or destroyed a large part of the buildings in the city.{{sfn|Pálfi|2015}} The Museum of Fine Arts building suffered damage to its roof, ruining the halls on the top floor, which prior to its evacuation housed the collection with the statuette.{{sfn|Balogh|1954}}<ref>{{cite journal |last=Genthon |first=István |date=June 1948 |title=Compte rendu du l'état de l'activité du Musée des Beaux-Arts (1945—1947) |journal=Bulletin du Musée Hongrois des Beaux-Arts |url=https://library.hungaricana.hu/en/view/ORSZ_SZEP_Kozl_002/?pg=35&layout=r |publisher=Museum of Fine Arts |location=Budapest |number=2 |page=36 |language=French}}</ref> Some of the remaining artwork was smashed or burned by the Soviets.{{sfn|Kovács|2015}} The museum did not hear of the evacuated art again until after the end of the war. In August 1945, they were contacted by the "Monuments Men" working in the [[Monuments, Fine Arts, and Archives program]] in Munich. They had been cataloging art looted by the Nazis, and at the [[Munich Central Collecting Point]] had works of art from the Budapest Museum of Fine Arts. The statuette, along with most of the other artwork, was returned to the museum by 1947.{{sfn|Kovács|2015}}

The statuette was exhibited in London in 1930.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reputed Bronze By Leonardo |author=Times Art Critic |work=The Times |date=30 January 1931 |issue=46665 |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=&docId=CS201665086&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |page=12 |ref=harv}}</ref> More recently, it was in New York, Washington and Atlanta in 2009, and in Los Angeles in 2010.{{sfn|NGA|2009a}} During the renovation of the Budapest museum until 2018, it has been on another tour: Paris<ref>{{cite web |url=http://museeduluxembourg.fr/actualite/cest-un-de-vinci-histoire-des-chefs-doeuvre-de-budapest-ndeg4 |title= C'est un De Vinci ? – Histoire des Chefs-d'œuvre de Budapest n°4 |publisher=[[Musée du Luxembourg]] |date=28 April 2016 |language=French |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Musée du Luxembourg}} }}</ref> and Mantova, Italy in 2016,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://gazzettadimantova.gelocal.it/tempo-libero/2016/08/31/news/durer-al-ducale-da-budapest-arriva-un-leonardo-1.14042101 |title=Dürer al Ducale Da Budapest arriva un Leonardo |work=[[Gazzetta di Mantova]] |date=31 August 2016 |language=Italian |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Gazzetta di Mantova}} }}</ref>, Madrid in 2017, and [[Buenos Aires]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://artdaily.com/news/93901/Exhibition-of-masterpieces-from-the-Museum-of-Fine-Arts-in-Budapest-opens-in-Madrid |title=Exhibition of masterpieces from the Museum of Fine Arts in Budapest opens in Madrid |last=Villarreal |first=Ignacio |website=artdaily.org |date=2017 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref=harv}}</ref>

== Attribution ==

[[File:Budapest Fine Arts Museum R01.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Museum of Fine Arts in Budapest]]
The statuette was attributed to Leonardo in 1916 by Simon Meller, the curator at the Budapest Museum of Fine Arts, due to its similarities to Leonardo's drawings.{{sfn|NGA|2009a}} Mária Aggházy summarised the attribution in the 1970s and 80s beyond the comparisons to Leonardo's drawings, by saying that the rider's composure matches the reported personality of the young to-be-king Francis I of France, that there is no armour or saddle as is suitable for French jousting, that the figure is wearing a royal-style crown ornament, and that the statuette was depicted in later French artwork for jousting.{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=34}}

The attribution has been widely accepted,<ref>{{cite book |title=Leonardo Da Vinci |chapter= Chapter Seven: 1503–1508 |last1=Clark |first1=Kenneth |last2=Kemp |first2=Martin |date=26 November 2015 |publisher=Penguin UK |location=London |isbn=978-0-14-198237-3 |page=ccxxxviii |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fXifCgAAQBAJ&dq=budapest |ref=harv}}</ref> more seriously than other sculpture attributions to Leonardo,{{sfn|Sturman|May|Luchs|2015|p=26}} and according to art historian [[Martin Kemp (art historian)|Martin Kemp]], is well supported.<ref>{{cite book |title=An Overview of Leonardo's Career and Projects Until c.1500 |editor-last=Farago |editor-first=Claire J. |chapter=Christo fanciullo |last=Kemp |first=Martin |language=English |year=1999 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8153-2934-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=fMDoImNWqHQC&pg=PA303 303] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fMDoImNWqHQC |ref={{sfnref|Kemp|1999a}} }}</ref> There is, however, some doubt, especially on the rider.

In the 1920s, following Meller's attribution, a dozen art scholars published their opinions about the statuette. Half of them, including [[Edmund Hildebrandt]], agreed with Meller's attribution, and the rest thought it was a later work by one of Leonardo's pupils.{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=56}} [[Ludwig Heinrich Heydenreich|L.H. Heydenreich]] wrote in 1954 that the statuette proves Leonardo's competency for casting in bronze.<ref>{{cite book|last=Heydenreich|first=Ludwig Heinrich|title=Leonardo da Vinci|date=1954|publisher=Macmillan|location=New York|volume=1|page=66|ref=harv}}</ref> In more recent publications, Martin Kemp noted the unusual lack of attention to detail on the horse's anatomy,{{sfn|Kemp|1999a}} which others have echoed due to the extreme bending of the horse's hind legs<ref>{{cite journal |title=Leonardo and sculpture: Atlanta and Los Angeles |last=Butterfield |first=Andrew |date=August 2010 |journal=[[The Burlington Magazine]] |volume=152 |number=1289 |jstor=25769741 |page=570–571 |ref=harv}}</ref> and a perceived lack of energy typical to Leonardo's other works.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smithsonian.com/arts-culture/leonardos-horse-141786173/ |title=Leonardo's Horse? |publisher=The Smithsonian Institution |date=17 September 2009 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Smithsonian Institution}} }}</ref> The quality of the surface modelling suggests that the bronze cast may have been made by one of Leonardo's pupils from a wax model of his,<ref>{{cite book |title=The drawings of Leonardo da Vinci in the collection of Her Majesty the Queen at Windsor Castle |last1=Clark |first1=Kenneth |last2=Pedretti |first2=Carlo |date=1968 |edition=2 |volume=1 – Text |isbn=0-7148-1343-5 |publisher=Phaidon |location=London |page=30 |url=http://bibdig.museogalileo.it/Teca/Viewer?an=336457_1&vis=D#page/104/mode/2up |ref=harv}}</ref>{{sfn|Clark|Kemp|2015|p=238}} as in one of Leonardo's worksheets he had made a note to himself to "make a little one of wax about four inches long" next to horse sketches.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The ''Battle of Anghiari'': A Speculative Reconstruction of Leonardo's Design Process |last=Farago |first=Claire J. |date=1996 |journal= The ALV Journal |volume=9 |url= http://bibdig.museogalileo.it/Teca/Viewer?an=339156_9 |page=[http://bibdig.museogalileo.it/Teca/Viewer?an=339156_9&vis=D#page/90/mode/2up 84] |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{Royal Collection|912328|Folio RL 12328}} Retrieved 28 March 2017.</ref> [[Kenneth Clark]], Martin Kemp, and [[Carlo Pedretti]] all suggested that the note refers to the Budapest statue.{{sfn|Clark|Kemp|2015|p=238}}{{sfn|Clark|Pedretti|1968|p=30}} Some believe the statuette is merely based on one of Leonardo's sketches.{{sfn|Bush|1999}} [[Giovanni Francesco Rustici]] has also been considered as the sculptor.<ref>{{cite book |title=European bronze statuettes |last=Radcliffe |first=Anthony |date=1966 |publisher=Connoisseur |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cWRQAAAAMAAJ |ref=harv}} via [[#{{sfnref|Aggházy|1989}}|Aggházy 1989]] p. 58.</ref>

Technical evidence from a 2009 investigation organised by the [[National Gallery of Art]] suggests that the statuette was cast near or after Leonardo's death in 1519 using the [[lost-wax casting|lost wax technique]]. The composition of the metal alloy is identical in all the parts of the statuette, apart from the modern pin used to attach the rider.{{sfn|NGA|2009a}}

[[File:Budapest Rearing Horse and Mounted Warrior, left side, by E.C.Rae.png|thumb|Reverse side of the statuette]]
[[File:Budapest Horse focus.png|thumb|NGA exhibition in 2009, left-to-right: Limerick horse, Budapest horse, New York horse, and the ''Mounted Warrior'' in the foreground]]
Equestrian statuettes with only slight variations to the ''Rearing Horse and Mounted Warrior'' have been discovered over the years. They are often referred to by their location. Particularly the ''Rearing Horse'' at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/195311 |title=Rearing Horse |publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|The Met}} }}</ref> and in the [[Hunt Museum]] in Limerick, Ireland,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huntmuseum.com/collection/rearing-horse-da-vinci-horse/ |title=Rearing Horse/ Da Vinci Horse |publisher=The Hunt Museum |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Hunt Museum}} }}</ref> have been considered as being by an early follower of Leonardo, such as [[Leone Leoni]].{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=49}} The three were exhibited for the 1969 Congress of the [[Comité International d'Histoire de l'Art]] as "Horses of Leonardo da Vinci" with reservation on their attribution.{{sfn|Aggházy|1971|p=[https://library.hungaricana.hu/en/view/ORSZ_SZEP_Kozl_036/?pg=62&layout=r 61-78]}} For repeat exhibitions in the US in 2009–2010, the National Gallery of Art investigation confirmed the New York and Limerick horses to be the result of techniques and alloys available only since the 19th century.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/aug/02/art-deciphering-the-da-vinci-code/ |title=Deciphering the da Vinci code |work=The Washington Times |date=2 August 2009 |accessdate=28 March 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Washington Times}} }}</ref> 

Another horse, a mirror image of the New York statuette with the horse facing left, was in London in the collection of art critic Pierre Jeannerat (d. 1983).<ref>{{cite journal |title=Leonardo da Vinci, Francesco I e il bronzetto equestre del Museo di Budapest |last=Aggházy |first=Mária G. |date=1972 |journal=Arte Lombarda |volume=17 |number=36 |jstor=43132107 |pages=96, 124–125 |language=Italian |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hopkirk |first=Peter |title=Attribution of Leonardo horses challenged |url=http://find.galegroup.com/dvnw/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=DVNW&tabID=T003&docPage=article&docId=CS152139609&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |work=The Times |issue=58614 |date=25 October 1972 |page=9}}</ref>{{sfn|Sturman|May|Luchs|2015|p=43}} The London statuette was exhibited in 1961–62 in London, Amsterdam and Florence as Leonardo's,<ref>{{cite book |title=Italian bronze statuettes: An exhibition organized by the Arts Council of Great Britain with the Italian Ministry of Education and the Rijksmuseum, Amsterdam: The Victoria and Albert Museum, London, 27th July to 1st October 1961. |date=1961 |editor-last1=Santangelo |editor-first1=Antonio |editor-last2=Pope-Hennessy |editor-first2=John Wyndham |chapter=Exhibit 20: Leonardo da Vinci, Rearing Horse |last=Jeannerat |first=Pierre |publisher=Arts Council of Great Britain |location=London |ref=harv}}</ref> but has since been attributed to sculptors after the 17th century artist [[Jan de Bisschop]].{{sfn|Aggházy|1989|p=56}} A similar statuette in the [[Speed Art Museum]] in [[Kentucky]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Warrior on Horseback |url=http://www.speedmuseum.org/collections/warrior-on-horseback/ |publisher=Speed Art Museum}}</ref> was once associated with this group of statuettes, but has since been attributed to Rustici<ref>{{cite book |title=Leonardo da Vinci |editor-last=Farago |editor-first=Claire J. |chapter=Biography and Early Art Criticism of Leonardo Da Vinci |last=Kemp |first=Martin |date=1999 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location=New York |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=XOZdXvzl83oC&pg=PA54 54] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XOZdXvzl83oC |ref={{sfnref|Kemp|1999b}} |isbn=978-0-8153-2933-6 }}</ref> or [[Willem Danielsz van Tetrode]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Fiammingo called Horse and Rider's maker |work=The Courier-Journal |location=Louisville, Kentucky |date=23 June 1974 |page=141}}</ref>

The provenance of the rider is disputed due to its size and lesser quality of work. Because the current attachment of the rider is modern, the horse lacks a saddle, and the rider is of smaller scale than the horse, the National Gallery of Art considered the possibility that the rider is a later addition. In their 2009 exhibit, the ''Rearing Horse'' was for the first time displayed separately from the ''Mounted Warrior'', which was placed beside the horse.{{sfn|NGA|2009a}} The [[Hermitage Museum]] in Saint Petersburg, Russia, holds a horseman statuette that shares the crude features of the Budapest rider.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warrior |url=https://www.hermitagemuseum.org/wps/portal/hermitage/digital-collection/06.+Sculpture/56460 |publisher=Hermitage Museum}}</ref> Titled ''Warrior'', it has been attributed to Leone Leoni or one of his followers, and may be based on the same model as the ''Mounted Warrior''.{{sfn|Sturman|May|Luchs|2015|p=29}}

